  <h2 id="what-is-eto">What Is Eto (干支)? The Japanese Zodiac System</h2>
  <p>The Japanese zodiac, called <strong>干支 (eto)</strong> or <strong>十二支 (jūnishi)</strong>, is a 12-year cycle where each year is represented by an animal. Originally from China, this system has been part of Japanese culture for over 1,400 years and remains deeply woven into modern daily life — from New Year celebrations to personality discussions.</p>

  <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(200px, 1fr)); gap: 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
    <div style="background: #fef2f2; padding: 1.2rem; border-radius: 8px; text-align: center;">
      <div style="font-size: 1.8rem;">🏮</div>
      <strong>New Year Symbol</strong>
      <p style="font-size: 0.9rem; margin: 0.5rem 0 0;">Each year's zodiac animal dominates New Year decorations and cards</p>
    </div>
    <div style="background: #f0f9ff; padding: 1.2rem; border-radius: 8px; text-align: center;">
      <div style="font-size: 1.8rem;">🗣️</div>
      <strong>Conversation Topic</strong>
      <p style="font-size: 0.9rem; margin: 0.5rem 0 0;">何年？(nan-doshi?) is a common question — "What's your zodiac?"</p>
    </div>
    <div style="background: #f0fdf4; padding: 1.2rem; border-radius: 8px; text-align: center;">
      <div style="font-size: 1.8rem;">📚</div>
      <strong>Kanji Practice</strong>
      <p style="font-size: 0.9rem; margin: 0.5rem 0 0;">12 animal kanji are practical vocabulary for learners</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p>The zodiac is not just cultural trivia — asking someone their zodiac animal is a natural, polite way to learn their approximate age without asking directly (a sensitive topic in Japanese culture).</p>

